WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.125 --> 00:00:02.125
Next, we're diving into near-drowning,

2
00:00:02.285 --> 00:00:04.344
also called wet-drowning, and what it
means from a

3
00:00:04.344 --> 00:00:05.744
respiratory therapist's perspective.

4
00:00:06.505 --> 00:00:11.045
Near-drowning occurs when a patient
survives a submersion event but develops respiratory impairment.

5
00:00:11.385 --> 00:00:14.484
The key problem isn't just water in the
lungs, it's

6
00:00:14.484 --> 00:00:16.344
what that water does to the alveoli.

7
00:00:16.944 --> 00:00:20.725
When water enters the airway, it washes
out surfactant and

8
00:00:20.725 --> 00:00:22.725
damages the alveolar capillary membrane.

9
00:00:23.405 --> 00:00:26.725
This leads to alveolar collapse, decreased
lung compliance,

10
00:00:26.985 --> 00:00:28.184
and impaired gas exchange.

11
00:00:28.545 --> 00:00:31.864
At the same time, fluid and inflammation
create a shunt-

12
00:00:31.864 --> 00:00:35.305
like state where blood is perfusing areas
that are not being ventilated.

13
00:00:36.064 --> 00:00:39.784
The result is hypoxemia that may not
respond easily to oxygen alone.

14
00:00:40.564 --> 00:00:42.744
Clinically, patients may initially appear
stable,

15
00:00:43.264 --> 00:00:44.744
but symptoms can worsen over time.

16
00:00:45.465 --> 00:00:48.104
You might see coughing, tachypnea,
crackles,

17
00:00:48.205 --> 00:00:49.845
or increasing work of breathing.

18
00:00:50.224 --> 00:00:53.724
One of the most important concepts is
delayed deterioration.

19
00:00:54.064 --> 00:00:59.505
A patient who looks okay right after
rescue can develop respiratory distress hours later

20
00:00:59.505 --> 00:01:01.084
due to evolving lung injury.

21
00:01:01.944 --> 00:01:05.745
From an RT standpoint, your priority is
assessing oxygenation and

22
00:01:05.745 --> 00:01:07.184
ventilation early and often.

23
00:01:08.184 --> 00:01:11.205
Monitor SpO2, respiratory effort, breath
sounds,

24
00:01:11.285 --> 00:01:12.165
and mental status.

25
00:01:12.824 --> 00:01:15.385
Watch for signs of fatigue or worsening
hypoxemia.

26
00:01:16.285 --> 00:01:17.925
Management starts with oxygen therapy.

27
00:01:18.224 --> 00:01:22.925
If hypoxemia persists, escalate to CPAP or
mechanical ventilation with

28
00:01:22.925 --> 00:01:24.165
a lung protective strategy.

29
00:01:25.144 --> 00:01:28.724
These patients behave similarly to early
ARDS, so think low

30
00:01:28.724 --> 00:01:31.205
tidal volumes, adequate peep, and avoiding

31
00:01:31.205 --> 00:01:32.264
further lung injury.

32
00:01:32.985 --> 00:01:34.684
Another critical factor is temperature.

33
00:01:35.544 --> 00:01:39.665
Many drowning patients are hypothermic,
which can complicate respiratory and

34
00:01:39.665 --> 00:01:40.084
cardiac function.

35
00:01:40.944 --> 00:01:43.565
Rewarming becomes part of the overall
management strategy.

36
00:01:44.245 --> 00:01:48.385
Red flags include worsening hypoxemia,
increasing work of breathing,

37
00:01:49.205 --> 00:01:52.565
altered mental status, and crackles that
suggest pulmonary edema.

38
00:01:53.544 --> 00:01:58.665
These indicate progression toward acute
lung injury or ARDS and require rapid escalation.

39
00:01:59.425 --> 00:02:01.184
For board prep, remember this flow.

40
00:02:02.044 --> 00:02:05.644
Water aspiration leads to surfactant loss,
which leads to alveolar

41
00:02:05.644 --> 00:02:08.604
collapse, decreased compliance, and shunt,

42
00:02:08.964 --> 00:02:09.904
resulting in hypoxemia.

43
00:02:10.705 --> 00:02:15.565
Management follows oxygenation support and
ARDS-style ventilation if needed.

44
00:02:16.365 --> 00:02:19.384
Bottom line, near drowning is not just an
airway event,

45
00:02:19.744 --> 00:02:21.205
it's an evolving lung injury.

46
00:02:21.845 --> 00:02:24.244
As an RT, your role is early recognition,

47
00:02:25.184 --> 00:02:28.725
continuous reassessment, and timely
escalation to prevent respiratory failure.

